1. What is the difference between a Business Object Model (BOM) and an Execution Object Model (EOM) / ROM (Runtime Object Model)?
BOM: A logical representation of the business data.
It is what the business users see in the Rule Maintenance Application (RMA).
It uses business-friendly terms.

Current Balance
Credit Score
Account is Active


EOM: The physical technical model (usually Java classes or XML schemas) that the rule engine uses during execution.
Blaze Advisor maps the BOM to the EOM to execute logic against real data.

public class Cust_Acct_Rec {
    private double cur_bal;
    private int credit_scr_val;
    private boolean is_active_flg;

    // Getters and Setters...
}

Rule Java:
---------
if (custAcctRec.getCredit_scr_val() > 700 && custAcctRec.isIs_active_flg()) {
    custAcctRec.setStatus("Approved");
}


The Business Rule (Using BOM):
-----------------------------
If the Credit Score is greater than 700
And the Account is Active is true
Then set Status to "Approved"
